T1  - Insider trading and the voluntary disclosure of information by firms
AU  - Narayanan, Ranga
JO  - Journal of Banking & Finance
VL  - 24
IS  - 3
SP  - 395
EP  - 425
PY  - 2000
DA  - 2000/03/01/
SN  - 0378-4266
DO  - https://doi.org/10.1016/S0378-4266(99)00043-6
UR  - https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S0378426699000436
KW  - Disclosure
KW  - Insider trading
AB  - We examine the voluntary disclosure policy of a firm where the manager has private information and opportunities to trade on it. The equilibrium disclosure policy ranges from full disclosure to partial disclosure to nondisclosure depending on whether the manager's pay–performance sensitivity is high, medium or low, respectively. In the partial disclosure equilibrium, good news is more likely to be disclosed early than bad news and insiders are more likely to sell than buy shares, two results for which there is ample empirical support. The likelihood and amount of voluntary disclosure increases with the manager's pay–performance sensitivity, firm quality, and the number of insiders privy to the information and decreases with market liquidity. Stringent enforcement of insider trading regulations induces more disclosure by firms whereas the short sales prohibition on insiders induces less disclosure.
ER  - 

